subSubSection.paragraph:
The type specimens of both
S. biclinius
and
S. marcidus
have been studied, and no differences between the two species were observed.
Stromboceros biclinius
was described from both sexes from “ Peru (Callanga, Cuzco ).” Two males and four females are at SDEI. All are labelled “Callanga, Cuzco , Peru ,” Coll. Konow,” “TYPUS,” and one male has the label “
Stromboceros biclinius Konow
, Peru .” The male with Konow’s id label is hereby designated the
Lectotype
. The other specimens are
Paralectotypes
.

Stromboceros marcidus
was described from a female from “ Peru (Callanga, Cuzco ).” One female at SDEI is labelled “Callanga, Cuzco , Peru ,” “Coll. Konow,” “TYPUS,” “
Stromboceros marcidus Knw.
, Peru .” This specimen is the lectotype , as stated by Oehlke and Wudowenz (1984) . Konow did not state the number of specimens available. A male at SDEI is labelled “Pachitea, Peru ” and cannot be part of the type series.

subSubSection.paragraph:
Konow (1903) described
S. parmatus
from both sexes from “Columbia (Sanjil).” Konow did not designate a holotype and did not state how many specimens he examined. Seven specimens, all with red “TYPE” labels are at SDEI. Oehlke and Wudowenz indicated that a lectotype was selected by D. R. Smith 1976; however, Smith did not designate a lectotype
prior to Oehlke and Wudowenz (1984) . The male labelled “Sanjil, Columbien, 6.01, Micholily [?],” “ Coll. Konow ,” “TYPE,” “
Stromboceros parmatus Konow, Columbia
,” is here designated the
Lectotype
,
presumably from San Gil town in Santander , Colombia . Three males and one male have the same data but lack a determination label, and two males have the same data except “5-6.01” and lack a determination label; all these specimens are the same species and are
Paralectotypes
.
